[1]
Date: Tue, 14 Jan 2003 08:27:09 -0500
From: Michael S Donnenberg <mdonnenb@umaryland.edu>

Mr Couger's remarks were very insightful and interesting. I am aware of at
least one study that examined the prevalence of STEC [Shiga toxin producing
Escherichia coli] infection in dairy cattle and antibodies to Shiga toxin
and O157 lipopolysaccharide in dairy farmers and their families (1). There
was a high prevalence of antibodies in the farmers and their families, and
the prevalence of non-O157 STEC infections in the cattle, as expected, was
much higher than that of O157 infections. The implication is that
subclinical infection with less pathogenic STEC may provide protection
against subsequent disease when exposed to more pathogenic strains.
1. Wilson JB, Clarke RC, Renwick SA, et al. Vero cytotoxigenic Escherichia
coli infection in dairy farm families. J Infect Dis 1996; 174: 1021-7.
--
Michael S Donnenberg, MD
Professor of Medicine
Head, Division of Infectious Diseases
University of Maryland, Baltimore
School of Medicine
<mdonnenb@umaryland.edu>
