[2]
Date: Tue, 14 Jan 2003 08:17:31 -0700
From: Andy Pavia <andy.Pavia@hsc.utah.edu>

Mr Couger's observations are intriguing. Recurrent _Escherichia coli_ O157
infection has been described, but it is extremely rare. In our experience
with over 330 children with hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS) followed
longitudinally, only a single case of culture confirmed repeat infection
with O157 has been documented. This seems lower than predicted for an
endemic region, but this is weak circumstantial evidence.
There have been a number of recent outbreaks occurring in regions where
many of the exposed may have been from rural areas (the large outbreak at
the Washington County fair in NY state, for example). I wonder if the
investigators looked at living on cattle farms, veterinary exposure, and
other measures of exposure to dairy cattle as potential risk/protective
factors. Evidence of a strong protective effect could prompt attempts to
study the components of the immune response in exposed/protected persons.
Key questions include the role of antibody to shiga toxin, to the products
of the LEE pathogenicity island such as intimin, or the hemolysins, and the
role of cell mediated immune response. Comments from field epidemiologists
with good data would be appreciated.
--
Andrew T Pavia, MD
Professor of Pediatrics and Medicine and Chief
Division of Pediatric Infectious Disease and Geographic Medicine
University of Utah
<andy.pavia@hsc.utah.edu>
